The '''Broadcasting Complaints Commission of South Africa''' ('''BCCSA''') is a string complaints authority established by the [[National Association of Broadcasters (South Africa)|National Association of Broadcasters]] (NAB) to enforce a Code of Conduct for [[television]] and [[radio]] broadcasts in South Africa. The Commission receives complaints from the public about offensive broadcasts and has the power to reprimand or fine broadcasters and to require the broadcast of a correction or apology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bccsa.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12&Itemid=26 |title=BCCSA Constitution |publisher=Broadcasting Complaints Commission of South Africa |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> The BCCSA is independent of the NAB and of government, although it is funded by the NAB and recognised by [[Independent Communications Authority of South Africa|ICASA]] as an independent disciplinary tribunal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bccsa.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=18&Itemid=32 |title=About the BCCSA |publisher=Broadcasting Complaints Commission of South Africa |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref>
