{{orphan|date=November 2014}}

'''Miguel Skrobot''' ([[Warsaw]], 1873 - [[Curitiba]], February 20, 1912) was a [[businessman]] Brazilian of Polish origin.<ref>[http://www.toczek.com.br/acervo/skrobot.htm Família SKROBOT - Colônia Muricy - Brasil] Toczek {{pt}}</ref><ref>[http://memoria.bn.br/docreader/DocReader.aspx?bib=240818&pagfis=2104&pesq= newspaper O Olho da Rua - 1911 edition] National Library of Brazil {{pt}}</ref><ref>[http://memoria.bn.br/docreader/DocReader.aspx?bib=214752&pagfis=1464&pesq= Magazine Almanach do Paraná - 1910s] National Library of Brazil {{pt}}</ref>

Miguel Skrobot was born in 1873, in Warsaw, [[Poland]], to José Skrobot and Rosa Skrobot. When he was 18 he migrated to [[Brazil]] and settled in Curitiba as a merchant.

He married Maria Pansardi, who was born in [[Tibagi]], [[Paraná (state)|Paraná]], to Italian immigrants, and she bore him three children. He kept a steam-powered factory where he worked on grinding and toasting coffee beans under the "Rio Branco" brand, located on the spot where today stands the square called ''Praça Zacarias'' (square located in the center of Curitiba). He also owned a grocery store near ''Praça Tiradentes'' (also a square in the center of Curitiba, where the city was born). He died an early death, when he was 39, on February 20, 1912.

