'''Sherkhan Farnood''' ({{Birth date|year=1963|month=8|day=15|df=yes}} – {{death date |2018|8|24 |1963|8|15 |df=yes}}) was an Afghan banker, [[Chairman]] of [[Kabul Bank]] until late 2010, which is [[Afghanistan]]'s largest private financial institution with over 1 million customers. Farnood held 28.16% of the shares in the Kabul Bank.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.kabulbank.af/html/Financials.html |title= Financials |accessdate= 2010-09-06 |work= |publisher= [[Kabul Bank]] |date= March 31, 2007 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100906124224/http://www.kabulbank.af/html/Financials.html |archivedate= September 6, 2010 |df= }}</ref> He also owned [[Pamir Airways]], in partnership with [[Khalilullah Fruzi]]/Frozi, [[Mohammed Fahim]] and possibly others.<ref name="WP3">{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/21/AR2010022104317_3.html?sid=ST2010090107315 |title= In Afghanistan, signs of crony capitalism (p.3)|accessdate=2010-09-06 |work=Andrew Higgins |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 22, 2010}}</ref> According to media reports, by November 2010 [[Da Afghanistan Bank]] insisted both Farnood and Kabul Bank chief executive Frozi had been removed from bank management;.<ref name="Ellis">{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2711446/CurrentIssue/80126/Why-Farnood-was-flushed-out-of-Kabulbank.html|title=Why Farnood was flushed out of Kabulbank|last=Ellis|first=Eric|newspaper=[[Euromoney]]|date=2010-11-07|accessdate=2010-11-11}}</ref> As of early 2011 both were effectively under house arrest and could not leave the country.<ref name="Partlow">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/31/AR2011013106130.html|title=Kabul Bank employees flee to Pakistan amid investigation into lending, officials say|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|last=Partlow|first=Joshua|date=2011-02-01|accessdate=2011-02-13}}</ref>
An ethnic [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/afghan-businessmen-leave-for-bonn-meet-1.431266 |title=Afghan businessmen leave for Bonn meet |quote=I am born [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]], but I speak [[Tajiki language|Tajik]], [[Hazaragi language|Hazara]] and [[Pashto language|Pashto]]. I am married to a [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]]. My mother is a [[Tajiks|Tajik]]. It is better you don't ask me about my tribal affiliations, because I am an Afghan. |publisher=gulfnews |date=November 29, 2001 |accessdate=2011-07-16}}</ref> Farnood is originally from the northern [[Kunduz Province]] of Afghanistan.<ref>[http://www.afghan-bios.info/index.php?option=com_afghanbios&id=2236&task=view&total=10&start=3&Itemid=2 Afghan Biographies: Farnood, Sherkhan Shirkhan Farnud]</ref> He studied chemical engineering full-time while simultaneously running a business in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]. During the 1980s and 1990s, he ran a [[hawala]], or an informal money transfer organization in Moscow.<ref name="WP3"/>
Farnood became a prominent [[poker]] player, he took part in the [[2008 World Series of Poker Europe]] ([[World Series of Poker Europe|WSOPE]]) and won his first bracelet.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.pokernews.com/poker-players/sherkhan-farnood/ |title= Sherkhan Farnood |accessdate=2010-09-06 |work= |publisher=Pokernews.com |date=}}</ref> Prior to his detention, he spent most of his time in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]], where he owned a number of villas under his name on [[Palm Jumeirah]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/21/AR2010022104317_2.html?sid=ST2010090107315 |title= In Afghanistan, signs of crony capitalism (p.2)|accessdate=2010-09-06 |work=Andrew Higgins |publisher=The Washington Post |date=February 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,704665,00.html |title= US Cuts Aid After Millions Siphoned Off to Dubai |accessdate=2010-09-06 |work=Susanne Koelbl |publisher=Spiegel |date=July 5, 2010}}</ref>
On August 24, 2018, Farnood died in prison at the age of 55, apparently due to natural causes.<ref>https://www.tolonews.com/index.php/afghanistan/former-head-kabul-bank-dies-prison</ref>
